Dan, I'd love to have you introduce yourself and share a little bit about your role now.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:07.000
That could be also the prior role too, but also something you like to do for fun.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:08.000
Sure.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:09.000
Thank you, Rachel.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:11.000
So as Rachel mentioned, my name is Dan Haidt.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:23.000
I currently am the Director of Continuous Improvement Analytics for Merck's Global Clinical Trial Operations organization, and I've been in that role for all of about two and a half weeks now.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:32.000
Prior to that, I was the Associate Director of Data Science for our marketing group, specifically around our hospital specialty and acute care brands,

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:42.000
so supporting data science and data analytics projects that were around things like patient journeys, patient segmentation, sales reporting, et cetera.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:49.000
And I work remotely from northern New Jersey, about a little over an hour west of New York City.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:56.000
And for fun, well, my wife and I have four very large dogs, so they certainly occupy a lot of our time and energy.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:02.000
When I'm not doing that, I do a lot of CAD modeling, 3D printing, things like that.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:07.000
So I'm always kind of tinkering and making or breaking something.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:10.000
What do you 3D print?

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:12.000
Right now, it's mostly organizational stuff.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:14.000
Like I have a toolbox in my garage.

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:23.000
I'm just slowly printing folders for screwdrivers, wrenches, what have you, just kind of trying to get myself a little organized.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:24.000
Cool.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:25.000
That's awesome.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:30.000
Well, we all love to see pictures of things that people have created as well.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:36.000
Well, Dan, I thought maybe we could start by talking a little bit about your career journey.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:47.000
Now, in getting to talk to you, I've learned you've had maybe a non-traditional career journey, going from full-time paramedic to leadership roles across really diverse industries.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:53.000
Could you tell us a little bit more about maybe some of the turning points in your career?

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:54.000
Sure.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:57.000
So I've always been in healthcare in some way, shape, or form.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:00.000
As you mentioned, Rachel, I started out as a paramedic many years ago.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:06.000
And from there, I have organically moved into supervisory management roles.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:13.000
And that's when I started to get bitten by the bug that eventually would be Six Sigma and process improvement.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:19.000
I spent a significant portion of my career doing that type of work for a variety of different organizations.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:27.000
I was with Quest Diagnostics for a period of time, which, for those not in the U.S., is a large U.S.-based laboratory provider.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:34.000
I was with UnitedHealthcare for several years, leading a team there and also leading projects there.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:40.000
Prior to Merck, I was with a medical device manufacturing company called BD, or Beckton Dickinson.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:44.000
And then, obviously, now I've been with Merck for a little over a year and a half.

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:51.000
Like I said, for the majority of my time, I've been involved with Six Sigma and more so the analytics side of Six Sigma.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:58.000
And obviously, you can see where that's a natural progression into more of a deeper data science type work.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:08.000
So for probably at least a decade or so now, I've been around some form of data analytics, data science, analytical programming, et cetera.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:20.000
Do you see some of those prior roles carrying over into the way that you approach your role today and leadership within that role?

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:21.000
Absolutely.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:25.000
I guess maybe even specifically like the experience as a paramedic, too.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:35.000
Yeah, I mean, I think that that experience helps almost kind of give you some perspective about things like urgency and, you know, priority.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:44.000
Obviously, you know, it gives you a skill set that lets you really determine what truly is important and urgent and, you know, what is a high priority versus a low priority.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:50.000
As I like to say, it's a lot harder to light your hair on fire when you've, you know, done that for a long time.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:56.000
So it kind of gives you a sense of calm almost in that scenario.

00:07:58.000 --> 00:07:59.000
I love it.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:00.000
Yeah, I agree.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:07.000
I feel like there are not a lot of analytical emergencies that compare to paramedic emergencies that can give you great perspective.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:17.000
I wanted to ask, Dan, for the people here who are not in your industry, who don't share your sort of professional experiences,

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:26.000
I was wondering if you could give us an example of the type of problems that your team tackles just so that we have some context about what you do.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:29.000
And that will help us ask more informed questions.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:33.000
And some of those might be like, what type of data sources do you work with?

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:34.000
Or what tech stack do you use?

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:38.000
What technologies are really essential to what your team does?

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:39.000
Sure.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:43.000
So I'll talk a little bit about more so about the role I'm just coming out of.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:45.000
Let me just because, like I said, I'm very new in my new role.

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:47.000
Oh, feel free to also talk about.

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:50.000
I probably won't be able to give you too much detail there.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:56.000
Yeah, I would say feel free to talk about your previous role that you were in for longer as well.

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:57.000
Got it.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:02.000
Yeah. So the team I'm coming from, we mostly work with patient claims data.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:09.000
We also work with a lot of sales data specifically around both our own products as well as competitor products.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:16.000
It's a lot of a lot of our data comes from external data vendors such as IQVIA is a large player in this space.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:20.000
And like I said, a good portion of our work was around patient claims.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:33.000
A lot of that was either segmenting patients or segmenting providers, trying to understand some cohort of patients that was either applicable for, say, a new indication for a drug that we were exploring.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:48.000
Is there a potential market here or is there a data gap for patients that have a particular social determinant of health that might have been limiting access to care that we would want to go pursue and try and ensure that those patients are getting care?

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:52.000
So ultimately we hand off those findings to our marketing teams.

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:55.000
And through that, a lot of it was, like I said, patient claims.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:57.000
It's all de-identified claims.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:05.000
Certainly there's nothing that can be re-identified or reverse engineered for trying to identify patients individually.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:12.000
But looking at them, probably one of the biggest challenges we often run into is that it's not 100% coverage.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:15.000
Most of our data sets are open claims data sets.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:21.000
So sometimes you don't really know what your coverage is for a particular cohort.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:23.000
You may have 30% of the patients.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:29.000
And I should preface it by saying my team was focused on U.S. therapy areas.

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:32.000
So you may have 30% of those patients in the U.S.

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:38.000
You may have 70%, depending on whether they were inpatient-focused therapies, outpatient therapies, et cetera.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:41.000
There was a variety of capture for claims in those spaces.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:48.000
That was always one of the big challenges that we ran into, was just trying to sort of project up the right amount, you know,

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:55.000
based on that subspace that, you know, we were working in in that given moment.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:56.000
Thank you.

00:10:56.000 --> 00:11:05.000
I was scrolling through the chat a little bit, and I'm really excited to see some people talking about signing up to be super fans for Posit Conf next year.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:11.000
So I just wanted to put a little call out to that, that I actually didn't know invitations went out this morning about that.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:20.000
But if anybody is interested in saving some money for the Posit Conference next year in Atlanta, there's the super fan tickets.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:28.000
But, Dan, something I would love to talk a little bit about, and I think this comes up quite a bit in the Hangouts,

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:32.000
but around collaborating with other stakeholders across the business.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:37.000
And something you taught me or were telling me about is to demand great charters.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:42.000
And I was wondering if we could spend some time talking a little bit about that and what that means to you.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:44.000
Sure.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:49.000
So I know it sounds a little cliche, but, you know, I think, Rachel, I shared with you that was something that, you know,

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:54.000
I took from a prior leader several roles ago was, you know, demand great charters.

00:11:55.000 --> 00:12:04.000
I think that sometimes it can become easy to sort of rush into a project or a particular task without necessarily having all of the facts

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:09.000
and all of the information that you need in order to, you know, move forward with intent.

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:14.000
And, you know, most folks here probably have that experience where, you know,

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:19.000
you see the scope of your project immediately start to balloon or you find out that, you know,

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:25.000
the project needs to be done by a certain date that you weren't aware of or some other constraint that you maybe didn't know about beforehand.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:30.000
So I think that that's really what something I try to, you know,

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:37.000
keep in mind whenever I approach any sort of project or any sort of conversation with a stakeholder around deliverables is,

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:42.000
you know, really developing that sort of charter document, you know, you know,

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:47.000
conceptually and physically, but it really becomes a contract.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:51.000
You're agreeing to all these terms of here's what it is that we need to deliver.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:54.000
Here's, you know, when did we need to deliver it by?

00:12:54.000 --> 00:13:00.000
Here's the various, you know, budgetary or personnel constraints that you may be working with, you know,

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:05.000
and any other relevant information that really sets those boundaries or those guidelines for that project.

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:10.000
And then you can always negotiate changes to your project charters later,

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:14.000
but then that also enables that tradeoff conversation, you know, where you could say, okay,

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:18.000
we understand we need to add this to our scope, but understand that's us.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:21.000
That's how that's going to change the schedule we already agreed upon, you know,

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:24.000
or whatever other constraint needs to be changed.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:30.000
I want to pause for a second and see if anybody has any follow up questions on that,

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:33.000
because I know that's something a lot of us face.

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:40.000
Making sure I'm giving time for people to unmute or raise their hand to.

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:49.000
Okay, well, Libby and I love getting to ask questions to everybody.

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:51.000
We want to hear from you, too.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:56.000
So if you have specific follow up questions or something you want to ask Dan, just a reminder,

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:00.000
you can put it into the chat or you could just raise your hand here as well.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:03.000
But Arsene, I see you had a question.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:05.000
Want to jump in?

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:08.000
Yeah, so this one isn't really on the topic from before.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:10.000
But first of all, yeah, thank you.

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:12.000
And thank you, Dan, for joining.

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:18.000
So my question actually is with respect to kind of the profile that I saw for you.

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:25.000
One of the things that you might deal with quite a lot more than many other data analysts

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:31.000
or data scientists is, you know, kind of the ethical concerns around using data

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:37.000
for both providing solutions to, you know, for patients and things like that,

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:40.000
but also for marketing and kind of that.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:47.000
So I'm just wondering if you could talk about any maybe tricky ethical situations

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:51.000
that you've dealt with, maybe not in this role, but maybe in prior things.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:53.000
So, yeah.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:55.000
I appreciate that.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:59.000
You know, I can say I'm fortunate in my current role and the role I'm just coming out of.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:03.000
Merck has a very robust, you know, data review process.

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:09.000
Essentially nothing can even go as far as our field sales teams without getting a rigorous review.

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:15.000
They certainly ensure that we're not sharing anything outside the four walls that we can't

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:21.000
and that we are being 100% ethically sound, if you will.

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:23.000
So, you know, we are fortunate with that.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:26.000
We know anything that is going to be – and like I said,

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:30.000
sometimes it's as simple as something that's going to face our field sales forces

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:33.000
or is going to drive a business decision.

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:40.000
It goes through a data review process and that review process with our internal teams.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:44.000
They certainly provide feedback, make changes, et cetera.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:47.000
So we are fortunate to have that available here, and that's something that –

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:53.000
so it takes some of the, I guess, ethical concerns sort of out of the equation.

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:58.000
I can say most of the – like I said before, most of what we deal with is all de-identified.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:03.000
There's very minimal features available at an individual level.

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:07.000
At most it might be a patient's gender, age.

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:09.000
We don't even have things like zip code, right?

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:14.000
Like sometimes you have to sort of infer that from a provider's information or some other aspect.

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:23.000
So, again, being very careful that we're not even touching data that could be linked back to a patient

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:28.000
or that could be used to re-identify a patient.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:33.000
Like I said, it's something that Merck is very, very aware of and very sensitive to.

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:35.000
Sure.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:40.000
So if it's okay, I've got kind of a two-part follow-up.

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:45.000
So one of them is – so when people talk about ethics in data,

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:54.000
especially, you know, in the age of like having all these articles and cases of breaches happening,

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:56.000
we tend to think of like data breaches.

00:16:56.000 --> 00:17:03.000
But I was thinking more in terms of like using, you know, in this case maybe PII,

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:10.000
and I think you did answer it, but using things like PII for marketing efforts

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:17.000
or for things like that that might cause a bit of an ethical conundrum for someone.

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:28.000
But I guess the other follow-up that might be useful here is besides those ethical kind of questions,

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:33.000
has there ever been a time when you were building a model and someone was like,

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:38.000
we don't have a variable that we could really use, but it's blocked because of PII?

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:44.000
And then if you could talk a little bit about how you kind of dealt with that, kind of the –

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:49.000
Yeah, that's probably a more common scenario, you know, to what I mentioned earlier,

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:53.000
because we don't have a lot of that – a lot of those features are variables, you know,

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:55.000
we often have to infer them.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:18:02.000
And one way we've done that is we have some zip code-based SDOH data, right?

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:07.000
So it's a lot of index scores based on, you know, zip three level, zip five level.

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:12.000
And again, you know, my scope was the U.S., so not getting into foreign zip codes.

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:19.000
But, you know, so what we would often have to do is say, okay, this claim for this patient,

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:25.000
well, we know they saw provider A, provider A's practices in this zip code,

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:34.000
and we're going to use the zip three regional level and pull in, say, the income index for that zip three region, right?

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:37.000
It's a very imperfect model, right?

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:41.000
There's a lot of model error when we do that, but it's either that or nothing, right?

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:44.000
So in a lot of cases that's our only option.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:47.000
Like I said, it does introduce quite a bit of model error.

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:51.000
And, you know, we built a model, just thinking back like about a year ago,

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:58.000
where we were able to get some useful information out of that model, but by no means –

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:04.000
in a perfect world, yes, we have all this, you know, PII that we'd be able to use to make a more informed model.

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:10.000
But, you know, again, to the point we made a few minutes ago, that certainly exposes a lot of that data.

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:12.000
Right now we don't even have access to it, right?

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:15.000
So it's not even a matter of we have it, we don't want to use it.

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:19.000
It's something that we often don't even have or usually don't even have.

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:21.000
Thank you so much for asking that, Arsenis.

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:27.000
And I – Yulia also had a question that was really along these lines, and it would be a great follow-up.

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:30.000
Yulia, are you available to ask?

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:32.000
Yes, I was just contemplating raising my hand.

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:34.000
Yeah.

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:38.000
I was thinking if we wanted to dig a little bit deeper and nerd down into it.

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:45.000
I think you mentioned that you've been building different types of segmentation models based on patient data.

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:50.000
And I was wondering if you have any clinical features of the patients that you used in those models,

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:52.000
such as diagnosis and EPS.

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:58.000
How do you handle the fact that there's a load of diagnosis out there?

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:04.000
Yeah, certainly that's something that we often do is when we are segmenting our patients and looking at –

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:08.000
obviously, like I said, most of our therapies are specific therapy areas.

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:16.000
So, for example, the team I'm coming from, we were focused on the HIV therapy area for the last eight months or so I was there.

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:22.000
So, my team was building models that were very specific to HIV-related diagnoses.

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:30.000
So, that's kind of where we always generally start is taking the patients that have any of the diagnoses that fall into that space

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:36.000
and then from there building out those various cohort segments based on the marketing team's needs.

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:40.000
So, it might be something around, say, patients that are switching between therapies

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:49.000
or patients that were therapy – treatment-naive, so they were on either no therapy or just started on therapy as part of that cohort.

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:53.000
So, that was where a lot more of our work tended to occur is looking at sort of that patient –

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:58.000
the end-to-end patient journey when it came to diagnosis, treatment, et cetera.

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:01.000
And, again, that's really the data that we have, right?

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:04.000
So, generally speaking, it's going to be diagnosis.

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:12.000
It's going to be, like I said, age, gender, provider, provider specialty, relatively high-level features like that.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:14.000
Can I ask a quick follow-up?

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:18.000
Did you ever do anything with kind of like multi-comorbidity in patients?

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:27.000
So, you know, your patient has five to ten diagnoses instead of just one, which will change their clinical nature quite a bit.

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:29.000
Yes, that's something that we did.

00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:38.000
Part of our models was looking at, you know, and specifically related, there's a subset of comorbidities that are of interest in the HIV space that, you know,

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:50.000
can either be contraindicated or may be more indicative of a side effect that's occurring in a particular patient cohort that's of interest to our marketing teams.

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:56.000
Okay, that was kind of building on clinical intuition or clinician kind of previous knowledge about the bill.

00:21:56.000 --> 00:21:57.000
Cool, thank you so much.

00:21:57.000 --> 00:22:01.000
And the other piece we also look at, too, is like drug-to-drug interaction.

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:11.000
You know, there's certain drugs that are commonly interactive with a lot of the medications in this space, so we often pull that in as well.

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:12.000
Thanks.

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:13.000
Thank you so much.

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:23.000
I see there are a few maybe like project management questions coming into Slido, but this one I'll ask first.

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:27.000
It was, how do you present your insights to the business?

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:33.000
And they added, the last mile is oftentimes where things fall apart.

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:39.000
How do we present our – well, I guess it's going to be dependent on the specific scenario, right?

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:47.000
You know, I personally am a big fan of, you know, the idea of data storytelling, right?

00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:55.000
And sometimes that can be a challenge depending on who the different people are that are in a particular project that are part of that conversation.

00:22:55.000 --> 00:23:02.000
You know, I think there's certain ways that are really good to present data, but you also don't want to get bogged down in the details, right?

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:13.000
A lot of your non-data-related stakeholders, your executive-level stakeholders, you know, they have a thousand emails waiting for them, a packed calendar.

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:19.000
You know, generally speaking, they want the highlights, and, you know, so I find it very helpful to get that out of the way up front.

00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:20.000
Tell them the so what.

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:21.000
Get them interested.

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:28.000
Present them, you know, essentially the minimum amount of data that you need to to get your point across and then move on, right?

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:36.000
It can be – I think a lot of us instinctively want to just present all the hard work we've been doing, right?

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:40.000
Here's what we've been doing the last three months, six months, whatever.

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:52.000
But as a result, you wind up just overloading the stakeholder with information that isn't of use for them or is too far down into the weeds of the details for them, and you wind up sort of clouding your message.

00:23:55.000 --> 00:23:56.000
Awesome.

00:23:56.000 --> 00:23:57.000
Thank you.

00:23:57.000 --> 00:24:05.000
Yeah, so Distilled, would you recommend, like, 30-second elevator pitch version of whatever your results are?

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:13.000
Do you feel like this is, like, a verbal thing you're talking to somebody, or is this more like two bullet points at the top of an executive summary type of thing?

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:16.000
That's what I was going to say, executive summary, right?

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:17.000
Load it up front.

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:19.000
Get them interested.

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:22.000
Don't be afraid to put stuff into an appendix, right?

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:26.000
Here's all the charts and graphs and detail that we've worked on.

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:28.000
Move it into the appendix.

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:31.000
Provide it as a pre-read or a follow-up.

00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:33.000
You know, put your executive summary up front.

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:39.000
Always some of your most important, you know, charts or graphs or whatever that you need to help, you know, back up what you're saying.

00:24:39.000 --> 00:24:42.000
But I find it's always helpful to get that executive summary up front.

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:43.000
Get it out there.

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:45.000
You know, here's what we found.

00:24:45.000 --> 00:24:49.000
Here's, you know, what we recommend or, you know, whatever the situation is.

00:24:49.000 --> 00:24:52.000
And, you know, again, whet their appetite, you know, if they want more info.

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:54.000
And that's where you have to kind of know your audience, right?

00:24:55.000 --> 00:24:59.000
You may have, you know, I've worked for VPs that were former engineers.

00:24:59.000 --> 00:25:02.000
And they'll be sitting there with their calculator, double-checking your math.

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:07.000
And people that are more, you know, sales-oriented, they just want that quick elevator pitch.

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:11.000
And, you know, their attention is distracted.

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:18.000
So, you know, really it does help to know your audience, to know what's going to be appealing for them and what they're going to be looking for.

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:23.000
Obviously, that comes with time, too, with working with a lot of the same stakeholders over and over.

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:28.000
Just being able to identify their specific personality or needs.

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:32.000
I was working on a Cordo doc this morning to share with our executive team.

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:39.000
And now I'm thinking, I need to go back and ask myself, so what, for the very top line of it.

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:40.000
Yeah.

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:41.000
It's tough sometimes, right?

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:46.000
I mean, like I said, you put a lot of time and energy and heart into, you know, developing some of these things.

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:52.000
And the last thing anybody wants to do is just put that into an appendix or delete that slide or chart or whatever.

00:25:52.000 --> 00:25:57.000
But, you know, if you take a step back and realize, is this really adding anything to my story?

00:25:57.000 --> 00:25:58.000
Yeah.

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:01.000
And sometimes you're not going to need that appendix at all.

00:26:01.000 --> 00:26:02.000
They're not going to care.

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:06.000
But if they do care and they do ask about it, you sure better have it, right?

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:08.000
Exactly.

00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:12.000
Well, I wanted to call in Allen.

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:15.000
Allen, I think you had a great question, or at least a talking point.

00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:21.000
And it might be veering a little bit towards a slightly different topic, but I think that that's great.

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:22.000
Yeah.

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:24.000
Dan, this is interesting to hear.

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:33.000
I think there are a lot of things in what you're doing that I've tried to do as well, either in clinical or now in a data role.

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:44.000
We have this problem constantly of trying to tell stories with claims data and are frequently or often met with the response of, well, we know this data is incomplete.

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:47.000
So how do we trust what you're really telling us?

00:26:47.000 --> 00:26:54.000
And that can, you know, the room full of engineers like doing their own math, they look up and they go like, well, where's the other 15 percent?

00:26:54.000 --> 00:27:06.000
So I wonder if anything from your experience has been particularly successful in giving confidence in the face of uncertainty while acknowledging that your data is incomplete or that your data does have flaws.

00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:11.000
What's helped your team to be successful there?

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:15.000
That is a valid challenge that we constantly deal with.

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:26.000
I think the things that we've found to be successful is a lot of times we'll do desk research on top of doing our data analysis to essentially validate some of our assumptions.

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:35.000
As long as we're in a reasonable ballpark, so even if it's something as simple as what's the number of patients that are on a specific treatment therapy?

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:46.000
If we do some desk research and see that the CDC says that there's this many patients that have that are on that therapy or that have that diagnosis and it's reasonably close,

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:54.000
then we will usually supply that as sort of a backup or a supporting piece of information.

00:27:54.000 --> 00:27:58.000
And usually we find that to be helpful.

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:03.000
And again, we'll use other sources too, like we'll use sales data.

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:16.000
Again, if we see that at least our composition of, say, facility types, for example, is similar for sales for a particular product and then the patients on that particular product,

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:24.000
then again, we know that the totals may not be exactly the same, but at least we could say, look, we're probably getting a pretty good representative sample.

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:25.000
Yeah.

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:26.000
Cool.

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:27.000
Thanks.

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:29.000
Yeah, thanks.

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:30.000
Exactly.

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:37.000
And acknowledging that, hey, we know this is imperfect, but we're going to try and project it as informed as we can.

00:28:37.000 --> 00:28:45.000
And we'll make sure that we don't accidentally over or under inflate something without calling it out.

00:28:45.000 --> 00:28:46.000
Yeah.

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:47.000
Awesome.

00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:48.000
Thanks.

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:49.000
Sure.

00:28:49.000 --> 00:28:50.000
Thank you.

00:28:50.000 --> 00:28:54.000
Geraldine, I see you asked a great question in the chat a little bit earlier.

00:28:54.000 --> 00:28:58.000
Do you want to jump in here next?

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:00.000
Sure, yes.

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:01.000
Hi, everybody.

00:29:01.000 --> 00:29:03.000
Hi, Dan.

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:05.000
Excuse my accent.

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:13.000
So I'm trying to actually jump into a role for data science, although I want to jump into something different.

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:17.000
I want to lean more towards financial analysis.

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:30.000
So I wanted to ask if you can please give us a history about your path that helped you prepare for this role, to execute it so well.

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:32.000
What did you do?

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:38.000
What could you have done differently if you were supposed to maybe get a time machine and go back to your past self?

00:29:38.000 --> 00:29:48.000
What tools do you acknowledge that are going to be best then that would have helped you improve your work even now?

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:50.000
I appreciate the question.

00:29:50.000 --> 00:29:59.000
You know, I think that for me, I've always found probably the thing that I've done, and I would go back and tell my younger self, definitely keep doing this.

00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:03.000
I like to think of a can't as a strong word.

00:30:03.000 --> 00:30:05.000
Never think of I can't do that.

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:06.000
I don't have that.

00:30:06.000 --> 00:30:08.000
I don't know how to do that.

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:09.000
Figure it out.

00:30:09.000 --> 00:30:14.000
If you are given a problem to solve and you don't know how to solve it, go figure it out.

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:16.000
Learn the task that you need to learn.

00:30:16.000 --> 00:30:20.000
Find the people that are going to help you solve it or are going to teach you how to do it.

00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:33.000
But really, the last resort is saying no, so really taking no and turning it into, okay, there's something I have to do in order to accomplish this task or this problem or whatever it is,

00:30:33.000 --> 00:30:39.000
and I'm going to go figure out what that thing is or what that barrier is and overcome it.

00:30:39.000 --> 00:30:45.000
So really taking that perspective of don't let anything stand in your way of accomplishing what you need to.

00:30:45.000 --> 00:30:55.000
And I think that really is something I found to be helpful, and I would, again, I would go tell my younger self, don't ever not do that.

00:30:55.000 --> 00:30:56.000
Okay.

00:30:56.000 --> 00:30:58.000
Thank you very much.

00:30:58.000 --> 00:31:05.000
I think my next question was going to be, like, what did you, like, what helped you prepare for this path?

00:31:05.000 --> 00:31:07.000
Maybe what courses did you take?

00:31:07.000 --> 00:31:09.000
What positions did you occupy?

00:31:09.000 --> 00:31:17.000
What projects did you work on, if you don't mind sharing?

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:19.000
That helped me prepare for my current role?

00:31:19.000 --> 00:31:20.000
Is that what you said, Jolene?

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:23.000
Yes.

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:29.000
Obviously, there's a number of different, I don't know if I can pinpoint any one specific project that prepared me for it.

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:40.000
You know, I think it was, you know, a combination of just having had the opportunity to lead projects that were in a specific space.

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:51.000
So, like I said, you know, earlier, you know, I started out working on a lot of projects that were process improvement, right, so Six Sigma, Lean, Kaizen implementations, et cetera, found that I enjoyed that.

00:31:51.000 --> 00:31:59.000
You know, so I guess that's probably part of the takeaway is, you know, don't be afraid to work on different projects in different areas and figure out what it is you enjoy doing.

00:31:59.000 --> 00:32:03.000
And then from there, you know, realizing, hey, I like doing this.

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:05.000
I'm going to go do more of this.

00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:11.000
And then started, you know, looking for projects and then eventually roles that were more targeted in that space.

00:32:11.000 --> 00:32:15.000
You know, I've never, I've often found that I'm domain agnostic.

00:32:15.000 --> 00:32:31.000
So, if you were to look at my resume or my LinkedIn, you'd see that, like I said before, I've gone from lab operations to health insurance operations to, you know, supply chain, now, you know, marketing, data science to back to continuous improvement, but in clinical trials.

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:55.000
Right, like I worked across a lot of different spaces just because, you know, I'm willing to and I enjoy really flexing across those different vertical, you know, it's more of a how I can apply my specific skill set or my interest in that specific space and figure out, you know, okay, how do I use this muscle or this, you know, how do I take this hammer and start looking for that nail that I'm going to hit?

00:32:55.000 --> 00:33:16.000
This is great. Dan, actually, I wanted to hop in and ask you, because I know that you had mentioned before, not for anybody here, but Dan has mentioned before a book called up is not the only way. And you have a great perspective on lateral career moves, sort of, instead of just focusing on up, up, up always.

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:28.000
I was wondering if you could share a little bit about that perspective, because it's sort of on this topic here, right? Of, like, what has prepared you for this really interesting career moving into a different area?

00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:43.000
Yeah, no, it's spot on, Libby. I mean, lateral movement is good. And it's not a bad thing. I don't think some people maybe have this conception of I have to move up, right? I have to move into my boss's role when they're done with it and their boss's role when they're done with it, etc.

00:33:43.000 --> 00:33:55.000
And realizing that, especially in larger organizations, or even across different organizations, there's nothing wrong with taking a lateral move. Sometimes you might even decide to take a step down if it's going to give you the right skill set.

00:33:55.000 --> 00:34:12.000
You know, so I think really thinking about your skill set, where you have gaps, or where you want to spend more time or learn more, you know, let that drive your decisions as far as roles, as opposed to just always saying, okay, now I'm a manager, I need to go become an associate director or director or whatever.

00:34:12.000 --> 00:34:33.000
And now I'm a director, I need to be a vice president, you know, like, you find a lot of people that get that mentality tend to chase title. And I don't know about you, but a title is not going to get me out of bed in the morning, right? I want to enjoy what I'm doing. I want to be excited about what I'm doing. I don't want to just wake up and say, okay, I got that title I've been shooting for, and now I'm going to shoot for the next one. You know, that to me is not very motivating.

00:34:34.000 --> 00:34:40.000
Are you intentional, Dan, about like setting aside time to think about that for your own career?

00:34:41.000 --> 00:35:08.000
Probably not as intentional as I should be. You know, it's something I just, I, I find I often have that conversation with myself as I'm preparing, like, for mentoring conversations, you know, I have a few folks that I've mentored in current and prior roles. And I find that that actually helps me because as I'm preparing for those, and, and just whether it's a direct report that I'm coaching, you know, it helps me a lot.

00:35:08.000 --> 00:35:14.000
Kind of reinforce some of that thinking for yourself as you're either talking through that or preparing for those conversations.

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:26.000
Yeah, no, I was just thinking for myself too, like, sometimes just taking the time to step back and think about, like, what are the other skills I want to grow into and areas to think about.

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:54.000
I was just going to say 1 thing that to that point, you know, that I found useful in the past 2 is, you know, I've had a couple of a couple of companies where I've used a career blueprint. Right? It sounds a little hokey, but to be able to sit down and say, here's my strengths. Here's my gaps. Here's what my, my manager thinks. Here's the feedback that I think my manager would identify for me, my peers, et cetera. And then helping just kind of use that to say, okay, what do I need to do? Right? Where do I need to spend my time and energy?

00:35:54.000 --> 00:36:04.000
From a learning perspective, do I need to go find a mentor in a specific space? Because I know nothing about it, but I want to work in that space, you know, whatever using that to really kind of.

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:09.000
Figure out what your roadmap looks like for the next couple of years or so.

00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:12.000
That's great.

00:36:12.000 --> 00:36:18.000
Jacob, you had, I think, 2 questions here in the chat. Do you want to go next?

