Any kind of tips on how to get past that?

00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:56.000
So, you know, and I know this is something that you probably find on many LinkedIn posts or blogs and whatnot, but it really is one page resume.

00:38:57.000 --> 00:39:10.000
Assume they're not clicking on links because, unfortunately, nowadays, especially when most roles are posted online, you know, they're oftentimes available globally or, you know, across a very large area of people.

00:39:10.000 --> 00:39:13.000
You're going to wind up with a ton of applicants for any particular role. Right.

00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:20.000
So chances are the recruiter that's screening is not going to click on a link and the manager is not going to click on a link.

00:39:20.000 --> 00:39:25.000
So it really is about trying to make it as concise, but as powerful as you can.

00:39:25.000 --> 00:39:34.000
You know, I found that a that probably one of the best the best or most effective techniques is leveraging your network.

00:39:34.000 --> 00:39:44.000
Right. So whether it's somebody that, you know, directly or, you know, somebody at a particular company, even just getting them to send in with a copy of the resume to a hiring manager to say, hi.

00:39:45.000 --> 00:39:50.000
You know, we've never worked together, but this is I work here with you, and this is somebody that I know, and they're really great.

00:39:50.000 --> 00:39:55.000
Here's the resume they already applied on your your workday site or your site or whatever.

00:39:55.000 --> 00:39:57.000
And, you know, hope you'll you'll give them a second look.

00:39:57.000 --> 00:40:02.000
I found those to be sometimes the most effective communication.

00:40:02.000 --> 00:40:07.000
So it doesn't necessarily have to mean that the hiring manager is a close friend of yours or friend of a friend.

00:40:07.000 --> 00:40:10.000
It can just be somebody, you know, that happens to work at that company.

00:40:10.000 --> 00:40:22.000
